'''Alan Harris''' ([[May 28]], [[1930s#1938|1938]] &mdash; [[January 25]], [[2020]]) was a British actor who played several roles in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' movies. Starting out as a model, Harris moved onto stage productions, and later motion pictures. For Star Wars, Harris' work was mainly behind the scenes; however, he has occasionally stepped in as an actor, notably portraying [[Bossk/Legends|Bossk]] in [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''The Empire Strikes Back'']]. Harris has the rare distinction of appearing as different characters in all three films of the original ''Star Wars'' trilogy (as well as as the first prequel, [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''The Phantom Menace'']]), as well as playing a [[Stormtrooper]] in all three films.

==Biography==
In the original [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']], Harris portrayed Leia's Rebel Escort,<ref name="Aveleyman">{{WebCite|url=http://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=65585|text=Aveleyman - Alan Harris|archivedate=20170716144534}}</ref> as well as a Rebel mechanic in the war room in a separate scene. Harris also portrayed a Stormtrooper.

In ''The Empire Strikes Back'', Harris filled in for [[Harrison Ford]] when it came to molding [[Hansicle|Han Solo's carbonite block]]. While Ford provided the mold for the character's face on the<ref name="226 Archive">{{InsiderCite|226|The Star Wars Archive|The ''Star Wars'' Archive}}</ref> so-called "Hansicle," as the item has since been dubbed in [[canon]],<ref name="Star Wars 50">[[Star Wars (2020) 50|''Star Wars'' (2020) 50]]</ref> Harris provided the mold for the neck down.<ref name="226 Archive" /> Furthermore, Harris was cast as [[Bislav Merril|Merril]] and later Bossk. Harris also played a Rebel on Hoth who is told to "prepare for ground assault" by [[Carlist Rieekan]] as well as a Stormtrooper on [[Cloud City]].

Harris' only onscreen appearance in [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']] was portraying a Stormtrooper again.

Harris doubled for [[Anthony Daniels]] inside the [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]] costume from ''The Empire Strikes Back'' onto ''Return of the Jedi''. The [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]] costume was made around him; various photos from the costume test exist. Harris later donned the Boba Fett costume while doubling for [[Jeremy Bulloch]] on the set for ''Return of the Jedi'', leading to a mixup with fellow costumed actor [[Trevor Butterfield]] who was portraying Harris' former character Bossk.<ref>{{WebCite|url=https://starwarsinterviews.com/original-trilogy/episode-v-the-empire-strikes-back/trevor-butterfield-lt-blount|text=Trevor Butterfield (Lt. Bound)|author=[[Dennis Pellegrom]]|date=2012-10|work=[[Star Wars Interviews]]|archivedate=20230205201435|nolive=1}}</ref> Harris' body was molded for the [[Carbonite/Legends|carbonite]] block of [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]]. Due to C-3PO and Bossk occupying the same scenes during Return of the Jedi, the role of Bossk was handed off to [[Trevor Butterfield]] while Harris stood in for Daniels' for lighting.

On short notice, Harris returned to the saga to double as [[Terence Stamp]] in [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''The Phantom Menace'']] due to Harris' resemblance to the actor.<ref>{{Blogspot|subdomain=bosskharris|url=p/interview_13.html|name=BOSSK IS ALAN HARRIS|text=Interview}}</ref>

Following his death in 2020, the first issue of the comic book series ''[[Star Wars: Bounty Hunters]]'' was dedicated to him.<ref name="Bounty Hunters">[[Bounty Hunters 1|''Bounty Hunters'' 1]]</ref>

